In our previous articles, we laid down a highly abstract, lightweight architecture in Part 1: Building a Type-Safe, Extensible Architecture and utilized it to construct a fully responsive modal system in Part 2: Implementing a Type-Safe, Animated Popup System. One of our core architectural choices was keeping CoreOverlayConfig micro-focused on Angular CDK's layout mechanics, completely decoupled from component-specific states.
Today, we are taking that lean foundation to implement a production-ready Toast (Notification) System.
Unlike a global, centered dialog, a robust toast system introduces uniquely dynamic requirements:

• Auto-dismissal with Smart Timers: Messages must automatically close after a configured duration.

• Interactive Hover Controls (Pause/Resume): For an optimal user experience, hovering (mouseenter) over a toast must freeze its expiration timer, and moving the mouse away (mouseleave) should resume it from the exact remaining time.

• Dynamic Stacking: Multiple active notifications must seamlessly stack vertically without overlapping.
Let’s see how elegantly these features map onto our refined architecture.
1. Defining the Domain: Config & Type-Safe Refs
Because our CoreOverlayConfig is micro-optimized to only know about CDK essentials, we extend it locally within ToastConfig to introduce metadata specific to notifications, such as duration, icon, and accessible politeness configurations.
Configuration: toast-config.ts
import { AriaLivePoliteness } from '@angular/cdk/a11y';
import { ComponentType } from '@angular/cdk/portal';
import { CoreOverlayConfig } from '../../overlay/core-overlay-config';export type ToastType = 'error' | 'success' | 'warning' | 'info' | 'processing';
export type ToastHorizontalPosition = 'start' | 'center' | 'end' | 'left' | 'right';
export type ToastVerticalPosition = 'top' | 'bottom';
export interface ToastData {
message: string;
type: ToastType;
}
export class ToastConfig<D = ToastData> extends CoreOverlayConfig {
politeness?: AriaLivePoliteness = 'polite';
announcementMessage?: string = '';
duration?: number = 3000;
icon?: string = '';
data?: D | null = null;
horizontalPosition?: ToastHorizontalPosition = 'center';
verticalPosition?: ToastVerticalPosition = 'top';
container?: ComponentType<any>;
}
Implementing the Smart Hover Timer: toast-ref.ts
To handle precise pausing and resuming, ToastRef tracks elapsed time using Date.now(). When pauseTimer() is triggered, it subtracts the elapsed span from the initial duration, leaving us with a precise delta to pass to setTimeout when resumeTimer() executes.
import { OverlayRef } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { CoreOverlayRef } from '../../overlay/core-overlay-ref';
import { ToastConfig } from './toast-config';export class ToastRef<T = any> extends CoreOverlayRef<void, ToastConfig> {
componentInstance!: T;
private _durationTimeout?: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>;
private _startTime?: number;
private _remainingTime?: number;
startDuration(duration: number): void {
if (!duration) return;
this._remainingTime = duration;
this._startTimer();
}
pauseTimer(): void {
if (!this._durationTimeout) return;
clearTimeout(this._durationTimeout);
this._durationTimeout = undefined;
if (this._startTime && this._remainingTime) {
const elapsed = Date.now() - this._startTime;
this._remainingTime = this._remainingTime - elapsed; // Calculate exact remaining time delta
}
}
resumeTimer(): void {
if (this._durationTimeout || !this._remainingTime || this._remainingTime <= 0) return;
this._startTimer();
}
override close(): void {
if (this._durationTimeout) {
clearTimeout(this._durationTimeout);
}
super.close();
}
private _startTimer(): void {
this._startTime = Date.now();
this._durationTimeout = setTimeout(() => this.close(), this._remainingTime);
}
}
2. Component Layout & Interaction
The ToastContainer binds our asynchronous lifecycle status hooks (Signals derived from CoreOverlayRef) into standard CSS hooks. It isolates the DOM interaction, wiring host-bound HostListener events straight into the smart timer methods we just engineered.
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component, HostListener, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { ToastRef } from '../toast-ref';
import { TOAST_CONFIG } from '../toast-tokens';
import { UiSpinner } from '../../../components/spinner';@Component({
selector: 'app-toast-container',
standalone: true,
imports: [UiSpinner],
templateUrl: './toast-container.component.html',
styleUrl: './toast-container.component.scss',
changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
host: {
tabindex: '-1',
'[id]': '_config.id',
'[class]': '_config.data?.type',
'[class.opening]': '_toastRef.isOpening()',
'[class.open]': '_toastRef.isOpen()',
'[class.closing]': '_toastRef.isClosing()',
'[class.closed]': '_toastRef.isClosed()',
},
})
export class ToastContainer {
readonly _toastRef = inject(ToastRef);
readonly _config = inject(TOAST_CONFIG);
get isProcessing(): boolean {
return this._config.data?.type === 'processing';
}
@HostListener('mouseenter')
onMouseEnter(): void {
this._toastRef.pauseTimer();
}
@HostListener('mouseleave')
onMouseLeave(): void {
this._toastRef.resumeTimer();
}
}
@if (isProcessing) {
<span class="toast-icon toast-icon--spinner" aria-hidden="true">
<ui-spinner [size]="14" [thickness]="2" color="#fff" />
</span>
} @else if (_config.icon) {
<span class="toast-icon" aria-hidden="true">
<i [class]="_config.icon"></i>
</span>
}<p class="toast-message">{{ _config.data?.message }}</p>
3. Orchestrating Dynamic Stacking in the Service
The core magic of managing multiple operational toasts on-screen simultaneously happens inside ToastService. Because CoreOverlayService inherently tracks active overlay instances via an internal openedRefs registry, we can dynamically offset each newly rendered overlay down or up based on the current length of the stack.
import { inject, Injectable, OnDestroy } from '@angular/core';
import { _IdGenerator } from '@angular/cdk/a11y';
import { OverlayConfig } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { CoreOverlayService } from '../../overlay/core-overlay-service';
import { ToastRef } from './toast-ref';
import { ToastContainer } from './toast-container/toast-container';
import { TOAST_CONFIG } from './toast-tokens';
import { ToastConfig, ToastType } from './toast-config';@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ToastService extends CoreOverlayService<ToastRef> implements OnDestroy {
private readonly _idGenerator = inject(_IdGenerator);
private readonly _defaultConfig = inject(TOAST_CONFIG);
open(message: string, type: ToastType, config?: ToastConfig): ToastRef {
const _config = {
...new ToastConfig(),
...this._defaultConfig,
...config,
};
_config.id = config?.id || this._idGenerator.getId('toast-');
_config.data = { message, type };
return this.openOverlay(ToastContainer, {
container: _config.container ?? ToastContainer,
config: _config,
createRef: (overlayRef, cfg) => new ToastRef<ToastContainer>(overlayRef, cfg),
providers: (ref, cfg) => [
{ provide: ToastRef, useValue: ref },
{ provide: TOAST_CONFIG, useValue: cfg },
],
attachContent: (containerRef, _component, cfg, ref) => {
ref.componentInstance = containerRef.instance;
ref.startDuration(cfg.duration as number);
},
});
}
protected _overlayConfigBuilder(config: ToastConfig): OverlayConfig {
const positionStrategy = this._overlay.position().global();
const isRtl = config.direction === 'rtl';
const isLeft =
config.horizontalPosition === 'left' ||
(config.horizontalPosition === 'start' && !isRtl) ||
(config.horizontalPosition === 'end' && isRtl);
const isRight = !isLeft && config.horizontalPosition !== 'center';
const offset = this.openedRefs.length * 48;
if (isLeft) {
positionStrategy.left('16px');
} else if (isRight) {
positionStrategy.right('16px');
} else {
positionStrategy.centerHorizontally();
}
if (config.verticalPosition === 'top') {
positionStrategy.top(`${16 + offset}px`);
} else {
positionStrategy.bottom(`${16 + offset}px`);
}
return new OverlayConfig({
positionStrategy,
scrollStrategy: this._overlay.scrollStrategies.noop(),
hasBackdrop: false,
direction: config.direction,
panelClass: config.panelClass,
disposeOnNavigation: false,
});
}
}
The Power of the Lean Architecture
By pruning CoreOverlayConfig down to its absolute bare structural primitives, we unlocked massive design benefits:

• Isolation of Concerns: The core platform service deals purely with anchoring elements. It remains completely agnostic to specialized behaviors like background timelines, macro tasks, or countdown sequences.

• Encapsulated Complexity: The intricate math behind tracking microsecond deltas and adjusting active positions belongs strictly to the Toast module.

• Flawless Type Safety: Downstream clients consuming ToastService interact with strongly typed payload payloads (ToastData) without polluting global configurations.
In the upcoming final chapter (Part 4), we will complete our custom overlay collection by diving into Connected Layouts to build an auto-flipping, boundary-aware Tooltip System utilizing standard Angular Directives and connected position strategies.
